<DOC><DOCNO>  ZF207-275-280  </DOCNO><DOCID>07 275 280.andO;</DOCID><JOURNAL>Federal Computer Week  Feb 13 1989 v3 n7 p1(2).andM;</JOURNAL><TITLE>Bush budget bolsters tech image: space, technology outlays matchReagan spending proposals.andO;</TITLE><AUTHOR>Brewin, Bob; Casatelli, Christine; Palmer, Scott; Taylor,Kymberly.andM;</AUTHOR><TEXT><ABSTRACT>George Bush's 1990 budget offers sharp increases in the areas ofspace, science and technology but gives the Pentagon virtually noincrease in spending.andP;  The proposal also raises the status of theWhite House science advisor, an as-yet unfilled position, to thelevel of the national security adviser.andP;  The director of theOffice of Science and Technology will be an assistant to thepresident for science and technology and will be an active memberof high-level inter-agency policy groups such as the EconomicPolicy Council.andP;  Bush's spending in the aforementioned areasconforms with the $14.9 billion proposed by Reagan's budget andincludes a $2.4 billion increase for NASA, to $12.6 billion, and a$361 million increase for the National Science Foundation's andthe Department of Energy's basic research programs.andP;  Bush viewsgovernment-supported research as a way to restore in US'scompetitiveness in the high-technology arena.andM;</ABSTRACT></TEXT><DESCRIPT>Topic:     National GovernmentBudgetingScientific ResearchExecutiveUnited States. Office of Science and Technology Policy.andM;</DESCRIPT></DOC>